---
import DocsLayout from "../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Callout, CalloutTitle, CalloutDescription, LinkCard, CardGrid } from "@refraction-ui/astro";
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";---

<DocsLayout title="Python SDK">
  <h1>Python SDK Reference</h1>
  <p>
    The EntDB Python SDK (<code>entdb-sdk</code>) is an async, type-safe
    client that exposes a <strong>single-shape API</strong>: there is
    exactly one way to perform every operation. Nodes are created from
    generated proto messages, unique-key lookups go through typed
    <code>UniqueKey[T]</code> tokens emitted by the
    <code>protoc-gen-entdb-keys</code> codegen plugin, and ACL /
    storage / aliases / idempotency are all keyword arguments to the
    same <code>plan.create</code>. Rename a proto field, regenerate,
    and every stale call site becomes an
    <code>AttributeError</code> at import time &mdash; no
    production-only failures.
  </p>

  <h2>Install</h2>
  <Code code={`pip install entdb-sdk`} lang="bash" />
  <p>
    Python 3.10+. The SDK depends on <code>grpcio</code>,
    <code>protobuf</code>, and the standard
    <code>google.protobuf</code> runtime shipped with your generated
    proto bindings.
  </p>

  <h2>Proto schema</h2>
  <p>
    The SDK is proto-first. Node types, edge types, and unique
    constraints are all declared directly in your <code>.proto</code>
    files. Every code sample on this page uses the same canonical
    shop schema: a <code>Product</code> with a unique
    <code>sku</code> and unique <code>barcode</code>, a
    <code>Category</code> keyed by <code>slug</code>, and a
    <code>BelongsTo</code> edge linking them.
  </p>

  <Code code={`// schema.proto
syntax = "proto3";
package shop;

import "entdb_options.proto";

message Product {
  option (entdb.node) = { type_id: 201 };

  string sku         = 1 [(entdb.field).unique = true];
  string barcode     = 2 [(entdb.field).unique = true];
  string name        = 3;
  int32  price_cents = 4;
  int32  stock       = 5;
}

message Category {
  option (entdb.node) = { type_id: 202 };

  string slug = 1 [(entdb.field).unique = true];
  string name = 2;
}

message BelongsTo {
  option (entdb.edge) = { edge_id: 301 };
}`} lang="proto" />

  <p>Three things to notice:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>(entdb.node)</code> / <code>(entdb.edge)</code> declare the
      message as an EntDB node or edge type and fix its numeric
      <code>type_id</code> / <code>edge_id</code>. The SDK reads those
      values off the descriptor &mdash; user code never types a
      numeric id.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>(entdb.field).unique = true</code> declares a unique
      constraint on the field. The server enforces uniqueness via a
      SQLite expression index on the payload value &mdash; a
      <code>Product</code> cannot be created or updated so that its
      <code>sku</code> or <code>barcode</code> collides with an
      existing row in the same tenant.
    </li>
    <li>
      The proto field number is the on-disk <code>field_id</code>.
      Renaming <code>sku</code> to <code>stock_keeping_unit</code>
      does not touch the disk format; only the wire / Python names
      change.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Build step</h2>
  <p>
    Generate Python proto bindings and the EntDB typed-key sidecar
    from one <code>protoc</code> invocation. The
    <code>protoc-gen-entdb-keys</code> plugin must be on
    <code>PATH</code>; build it once from this repository:
  </p>

  <Code code={`cd tools/protoc-gen-entdb-keys
make build       # produces bin/protoc-gen-entdb-keys
make install     # copies into $GOBIN (which should be on PATH)`} lang="bash" />

  <Callout variant="info">
    <CalloutTitle>Plugin on PATH</CalloutTitle>
    <CalloutDescription>
      If <code>protoc</code> cannot find <code>protoc-gen-entdb-keys</code>,
    every <code>--entdb-keys_out</code> invocation fails with
    <code>program not found</code>. After <code>make install</code>,
    verify with <code>which protoc-gen-entdb-keys</code>. The plugin
    is a standalone Go binary — no Python runtime involvement.
    </CalloutDescription>
  </Callout>

  <Code code={`protoc \\
  --python_out=. \\
  --entdb-keys_out=. \\
  -I . -I path/to/entdb/proto \\
  schema.proto`} lang="bash" />

  <p><code>protoc</code> emits:</p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>File</th><th>Contents</th></tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>schema_pb2.py</code></td>
      <td>
        Standard generated classes: <code>schema_pb2.Product</code>,
        <code>schema_pb2.Category</code>,
        <code>schema_pb2.BelongsTo</code>.
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>schema_entdb.py</code></td>
      <td>
        EntDB typed <code>UniqueKey</code> tokens, one class per
        message with unique fields.
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <p>The sidecar looks like this:</p>
  <Code code={`# Code generated by protoc-gen-entdb-keys. DO NOT EDIT.
from entdb_sdk import UniqueKey

class ProductKeys:
    sku     = UniqueKey[str](type_id=201, field_id=1, name="sku")
    barcode = UniqueKey[str](type_id=201, field_id=2, name="barcode")

class CategoryKeys:
    slug    = UniqueKey[str](type_id=202, field_id=1, name="slug")`} lang="python" />

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <CalloutTitle>Typed tokens are the ONLY lookup form</CalloutTitle>
    <CalloutDescription>
      <code>UniqueKey</code> is the single canonical path for
    unique-field lookups. There is no string form of
    <code>get_by_key</code>. Rename <code>sku</code> to
    <code>stock_keeping_unit</code> in proto, regenerate, and every
    stale <code>ProductKeys.sku</code> reference is an
    <code>AttributeError</code> at import time &mdash; you find out
    at the first call site, not in production.
    </CalloutDescription>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Connecting</h2>
  <Code code={`import asyncio
from entdb_sdk import DbClient, register_proto_schema, Actor

import schema_pb2
from schema_entdb import ProductKeys, CategoryKeys

async def main():
    async with DbClient(
        "api.example.com:443",
        api_key="sk-prod-...",
        secure=True,
    ) as db:
        # Register the generated proto module once per process.
        register_proto_schema(schema_pb2)

        # Bind tenant + actor once; every call from \`alice\` is short.
        alice = db.tenant("acme").actor(Actor.user("alice"))
        ...

asyncio.run(main())`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    <code>DbClient</code> is an async context manager. Call
    <code>register_proto_schema(schema_pb2)</code> once after entering
    the context to populate the SDK's schema registry from the
    generated module's <code>FileDescriptor</code>. The
    <code>tenant(...).actor(...)</code> pair returns an
    <code>ActorScope</code> that captures tenant + actor so every
    read or write is short.
  </p>

  <h2>Creating nodes</h2>
  <p>
    <code>plan.create(msg, *, acl=None, storage=Tenant())</code> is
    the only way to create a node. The proto message determines the
    type (via its <code>(entdb.node)</code> option) and the payload
    (only fields explicitly set on the message are sent).
  </p>

  <Code code={`from entdb_sdk import ACLEntry, Actor, Permission, Mailbox, Public
import schema_pb2

plan = alice.plan()

# Default: tenant storage with the type's default ACL.
plan.create(schema_pb2.Product(
    sku="WIDGET-1",
    barcode="0123456789012",
    name="Widget",
    price_cents=1999,
    stock=50,
))

# With an explicit ACL.
plan.create(
    schema_pb2.Product(sku="WIDGET-2", name="Widget Plus"),
    acl=[
        ACLEntry(grantee=str(Actor.user("bob")), permission=Permission.READ),
        ACLEntry(grantee=str(Actor.group("merchants")), permission=Permission.WRITE),
    ],
)

# Private per-user mailbox.
plan.create(
    schema_pb2.Product(sku="WIDGET-3", name="Internal draft"),
    storage=Mailbox(user_id="alice"),
)

# Cross-tenant public catalogue.
plan.create(
    schema_pb2.Product(sku="WIDGET-4", name="Reference SKU"),
    storage=Public(),
)

await plan.commit()`} lang="python" />

  <h2>Looking up by id</h2>
  <Code code={`import schema_pb2

product = await alice.get(schema_pb2.Product, "node-42")
if product is None:
    print("not found")
else:
    print(product.node_id, product.payload)`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    The first argument is the proto message <em>class</em>, used as
    the type witness; the SDK reads the <code>type_id</code> from
    its descriptor at call time.
  </p>

  <h2>Looking up by unique key</h2>
  <Code code={`from schema_entdb import ProductKeys

product = await alice.get_by_key(ProductKeys.sku, "WIDGET-1")

# Different unique field on the same type.
by_barcode = await alice.get_by_key(ProductKeys.barcode, "0123456789012")

# Type-checker error: ProductKeys.sku is UniqueKey[str], not int.
# product = await alice.get_by_key(ProductKeys.sku, 12345)`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    The pitch: <strong>rename <code>sku</code> to
    <code>stock_keeping_unit</code></strong> in proto, regenerate,
    and <code>ProductKeys.sku</code> becomes
    <code>ProductKeys.stock_keeping_unit</code> in the sidecar. Every
    stale call site is an <code>AttributeError</code> the moment the
    module imports &mdash; no stale string literals waiting to blow up
    in production.
  </p>

  <h2>Querying with operators</h2>
  <p>
    <code>scope.query</code> takes a MongoDB-style filter dict. Field
    names are <strong>proto field names</strong> (not field ids); the
    server resolves them using the schema registry at the ingress
    boundary.
  </p>

  <Code code={`import schema_pb2

# price_cents >= 1000 AND stock in a set
results = await alice.query(schema_pb2.Product, filter={
    "price_cents": {"$gte": 1000},
    "stock":       {"$in": [10, 25, 50]},
})

# name prefix match
hits = await alice.query(schema_pb2.Product, filter={
    "name": {"$like": "Widget%"},
})

# top-level $or
either = await alice.query(schema_pb2.Product, filter={
    "$or": [
        {"price_cents": {"$lt": 500}},
        {"stock": 0},
    ],
})`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    Supported operators: <code>$eq</code> (default), <code>$ne</code>,
    <code>$gt</code>, <code>$gte</code>, <code>$lt</code>,
    <code>$lte</code>, <code>$in</code>, <code>$nin</code>,
    <code>$like</code>, <code>$between</code>, plus top-level
    <code>$and</code> and <code>$or</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Full-text search</h2>
  <p>
    <code>scope.search(node_type, query, *, limit=50, offset=0)</code>
    runs an FTS5 match expression across every field declared with
    <code>(entdb.field).searchable = true</code>. Results are
    ordered by relevance and ACL-filtered server-side, so the caller
    only ever sees nodes the actor is allowed to read.
  </p>

  <Code code={`// schema.proto — mark fields searchable
message Product {
  option (entdb.node) = { type_id: 201 };

  string sku  = 1 [(entdb.field).unique = true];
  string name        = 3 [(entdb.field).searchable = true];
  string description = 6 [(entdb.field).searchable = true];
}`} lang="proto" />

  <Code code={`# Single term, phrase, prefix, and boolean queries are all valid FTS5.
hits = await alice.search(schema_pb2.Product, "widget")
phrase = await alice.search(schema_pb2.Product, '"claw hammer"')
prefix = await alice.search(schema_pb2.Product, "wid*")
boolean = await alice.search(schema_pb2.Product, "hammer OR wrench NOT broken")

# Pagination via limit / offset.
page2 = await alice.search(
    schema_pb2.Product, "tool", limit=20, offset=20,
)`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    Underlying call is <code>DbClient.search_nodes(node_type, tenant,
    actor, query, *, limit, offset)</code>. A type without any
    <code>searchable</code> field returns an empty list rather than
    raising — the FTS5 virtual table just has nothing indexed.
  </p>

  <h2>Updating</h2>
  <p>
    <code>plan.update(node_id, msg)</code> sends a partial patch.
    <strong>Only fields explicitly set on the proto message become
    the patch</strong>; unset fields are left untouched on the server:
  </p>

  <Code code={`plan = alice.plan()

# Only price_cents is set → patch = {"price_cents": 1499}.
plan.update("node-42", schema_pb2.Product(price_cents=1499))

await plan.commit()`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    The type is read from the message's <code>(entdb.node)</code>
    option, so there is no separate <code>type_id</code> argument. To
    clear a scalar to its zero value, use a proto3 <code>optional</code>
    field so the wire format can distinguish "unset" from "explicitly
    zero".
  </p>

  <h2>Deleting</h2>
  <Code code={`import schema_pb2

plan = alice.plan()
plan.delete(schema_pb2.Product, "node-42")
await plan.commit()`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    <code>plan.delete</code> takes the proto message <em>class</em>
    as the type witness, not an instance. The SDK resolves
    <code>type_id</code> without guessing.
  </p>

  <h2>Edges</h2>
  <Code code={`import schema_pb2

plan = alice.plan()

# Alias lets the edge reference a node created in the same plan.
plan.create(schema_pb2.Category(slug="hand-tools", name="Hand tools"),
            as_="hand-tools")

plan.create(schema_pb2.Product(sku="HAMMER-01", name="Claw hammer"),
            as_="hammer")

# Link the product to the category.
plan.edge_create(schema_pb2.BelongsTo, "$hammer", "$hand-tools")

await plan.commit()

# Later: unlink them.
plan2 = alice.plan()
plan2.edge_delete(schema_pb2.BelongsTo, "product-id-42", "category-id-9")
await plan2.commit()`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    The <code>edge_id</code> is read from the edge message's
    <code>(entdb.edge)</code> option. Aliases prefixed with
    <code>$</code> refer to nodes created earlier in the same plan.
  </p>

  <h2>Edge traversal</h2>
  <p>
    <code>scope.edges_out(node_id, edge_type=...)</code> returns the
    raw outgoing edges from a node;
    <code>scope.edges_in(node_id, edge_type=...)</code> returns the
    incoming edges. Both differ from <code>scope.connected(...)</code>:
    <code>connected</code> dereferences each edge and returns the
    nodes on the far side, while <code>edges_out</code> /
    <code>edges_in</code> return the edges themselves with their
    metadata (<code>edge_id</code>, <code>from_id</code>,
    <code>to_id</code>, <code>props</code>).
  </p>

  <Code code={`from schema_entdb import BelongsToEdge  # generated EdgeTypeDef witness

# All outgoing BelongsTo edges from a product.
out_edges = await alice.edges_out("product-id-42", edge_type=schema_pb2.BelongsTo)
for e in out_edges:
    print(e.edge_id, e.from_id, "→", e.to_id, e.props)

# All incoming BelongsTo edges into a category.
in_edges = await alice.edges_in("category-hand-tools", edge_type=schema_pb2.BelongsTo)

# Omit edge_type to fetch every edge type touching the node.
all_out = await alice.edges_out("product-id-42")`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    Use <code>edges_out</code> / <code>edges_in</code> when you need
    edge properties or want to walk a multi-hop graph manually; use
    <code>connected</code> when you only care about the destination
    nodes and want them ACL-filtered and paginated in a single
    round-trip.
  </p>

  <h2>Atomic plans</h2>
  <p>
    A <code>plan</code> batches operations into a single atomic
    commit. Either every op applies or none do &mdash; the WAL commit
    is all-or-nothing:
  </p>

  <Code code={`plan = alice.plan()

plan.create(schema_pb2.Product(
    sku="HAMMER-01", barcode="0000000000017",
    name="Claw hammer", price_cents=2499, stock=100,
), as_="hammer")
plan.create(schema_pb2.Product(
    sku="WRENCH-01", barcode="0000000000024",
    name="Adjustable wrench", price_cents=1799, stock=50,
), as_="wrench")
plan.update("old-product-id", schema_pb2.Product(stock=0))
plan.delete(schema_pb2.Product, "discontinued-id")
plan.edge_create(schema_pb2.BelongsTo, "$hammer", "category-hand-tools")
plan.edge_create(schema_pb2.BelongsTo, "$wrench", "category-hand-tools")

result = await plan.commit()
print("created", result.created_node_ids)`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    A plan cannot be reused after <code>commit</code>; create a fresh
    one for subsequent operations.
  </p>

  <h2>Idempotency keys</h2>
  <Code code={`plan = alice.plan(idempotency_key="order-12345")
plan.create(schema_pb2.Product(sku="LIMITED-ED-01", name="Limited Edition"))
result = await plan.commit()`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    Retrying the same <code>idempotency_key</code> returns the same
    <code>result</code> rather than creating duplicates. The server
    short-circuits the second attempt and hands back the original
    <code>created_node_ids</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Receipt status</h2>
  <p>
    <code>plan.commit()</code> returns as soon as the WAL append is
    durable — the <code>Applier</code> may not have materialized the
    write into SQLite yet. For workflows that need to know whether a
    write has been applied without blocking on
    <code>wait_for_offset</code>, poll the receipt by its
    idempotency key:
  </p>

  <Code code={`plan = alice.plan(idempotency_key="order-12345")
plan.create(schema_pb2.Product(sku="LIMITED-ED-01", name="Limited Edition"))
result = await plan.commit()

# Status transitions: PENDING → APPLIED (or FAILED on apply error).
status = await db.get_receipt_status("acme", "order-12345")
if status == "APPLIED":
    print("materialized into SQLite")
elif status == "PENDING":
    print("still in the WAL, applier hasn't caught up")
elif status == "FAILED":
    print("apply failed — see server logs")`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    The receipt is keyed by <code>(tenant_id, idempotency_key)</code>,
    so a plan committed without an explicit key still has a generated
    UUID under <code>result.receipt.idempotency_key</code> that you
    can pass back. Prefer <code>wait_for_offset</code> when you need
    a blocking guarantee, and <code>get_receipt_status</code> for
    fire-and-poll workflows where the caller cannot tie up a
    connection.
  </p>

  <h2>Error handling</h2>
  <p>All SDK errors subclass <code>EntDbError</code>; match the typed variants:</p>

  <Code code={`from entdb_sdk import (
    UniqueConstraintError,
    RateLimitError,
    AccessDeniedError,
    ValidationError,
)

try:
    await plan.commit()
except UniqueConstraintError as e:
    print(f"duplicate value for field_id={e.field_id}: {e.value!r}")
except RateLimitError as e:
    print(f"rate limited, retry after {e.retry_after_ms} ms")
    await asyncio.sleep(e.retry_after_ms / 1000)
except AccessDeniedError as e:
    print(f"access denied: {e.actor} on {e.resource_id}")
except ValidationError as e:
    print(f"validation failed: {e}")`} lang="python" />

  <Callout variant="info">
    <CalloutTitle>Rate-limit retry hint</CalloutTitle>
    <CalloutDescription>
      <code>RateLimitError.retry_after_ms</code> is a server-side hint
    honouring all three quota layers (monthly writes, per-tenant RPS,
    per-user RPS). Treat it as the minimum wait; exponential backoff
    capped at that value is the standard pattern.
    </CalloutDescription>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Group management</h2>
  <p>
    Groups are first-class actors: any ACL entry that grants to a
    <code>group:</code> principal cascades to every current member.
    Add and remove members through
    <code>db.group_add(group_id, member_actor_id, tenant, actor)</code>
    and
    <code>db.group_remove(group_id, member_actor_id, tenant, actor)</code>.
    The actor performing the change must be an admin of the tenant.
  </p>

  <Code code={`from entdb_sdk import Actor, Permission

# Create a "merchants" group by sharing nodes to it — the group is
# materialized lazily on first reference. Membership is tracked
# server-side, separately from the ACL graph.
await db.group_add(
    group_id="merchants",
    member_actor_id=str(Actor.user("alice")),
    tenant_id="acme",
    actor="user:admin",
    role="member",       # or "admin" for delegated group management
)
await db.group_add("merchants", str(Actor.user("bob")), "acme", "user:admin")

# Share a node to the whole group in one call. Alice and Bob both
# now have WRITE access via their merchants membership.
await alice.share(
    "product-id-42",
    Actor.group("merchants"),
    Permission.WRITE,
)

# Remove Bob — the existing share is unaffected for everyone else.
await db.group_remove("merchants", str(Actor.user("bob")), "acme", "user:admin")`} lang="python" />

  <p>
    Both methods return <code>True</code> on success and
    <code>False</code> when the membership did not exist (idempotent
    no-op). To list all members of a group or all groups an actor
    belongs to, query the global store via the admin gRPC surface;
    these are not exposed on <code>ActorScope</code> because they
    cross tenant boundaries.
  </p>

  <h2>Storage modes</h2>
  <p>
    Every node has an <strong>immutable</strong> storage mode chosen
    at creation time. Pass the appropriate descriptor to
    <code>storage=</code>:
  </p>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Mode</th><th>Location</th><th>Use case</th></tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>Tenant()</code> (default)</td>
      <td><code>tenant.db</code></td>
      <td>Shared, ACL-controlled team data</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>Mailbox(user_id=...)</code></td>
      <td><code>user_&lt;user_id&gt;.db</code></td>
      <td>Per-user private data &mdash; drafts, personal notes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>Public()</code></td>
      <td><code>public.db</code></td>
      <td>Cross-tenant shared content &mdash; catalogues, templates</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <CalloutTitle>Storage mode is immutable</CalloutTitle>
    <CalloutDescription>
      Once a node is written, it cannot be moved between files. Pick
    deliberately at create time. Edges may only point from
    more-private to equal-or-less-private storage
    (<code>mailbox → tenant</code> is allowed;
    <code>tenant → mailbox</code> is rejected at write time).
    </CalloutDescription>
  </Callout>

  <h2>CLI</h2>
  <p>
    The <code>entdb</code> command handles proto schema workflows
    (lint, compatibility check, init snapshot):
  </p>
  <Code code={`entdb lint schema.proto
entdb init schema.proto            # freeze baseline in .entdb/snapshot.json
entdb check schema.proto           # compare proto against baseline`} lang="bash" />

  <p>
    For raw data access from the terminal (<code>get</code>,
    <code>put</code>, <code>query</code>), use the Go CLI
    (<code>entdb</code> installed from the Go SDK) with a compiled
    <code>--proto-descriptor</code> descriptor set &mdash; it names
    types by proto message name, not numeric <code>type_id</code>:
  </p>
  <Code code={`protoc --descriptor_set_out=schema.protoset schema.proto

entdb get localhost:50051 \\
  --tenant=acme --actor=user:alice \\
  --proto-descriptor=schema.protoset \\
  --type=Product --node-id=node-42

entdb query localhost:50051 \\
  --tenant=acme --actor=user:alice \\
  --proto-descriptor=schema.protoset \\
  --type=Product \\
  --filter='{"price_cents":{"$gte":1000}}'`} lang="bash" />

  <h2>Python ↔ Go parity</h2>
  <p>
    The Python and Go SDKs mirror each other operation for operation.
    Teams running both can copy call shapes straight across:
  </p>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Operation</th><th>Python</th><th>Go</th></tr>
